A '''rump party''' is a [[political party]] that is formed by the remaining body of supporters and leaders who do not support a breakaway group who merge with or form another new party. The rump party can have the name of the original party, or a new name.
Examples: * The pro-[[protectionism]] [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] in the UK after the breakaway of the [[free trade]] [[Peelite]] faction in 1846 over the repeal of the [[corn laws]]. * [[United Labour Party (New Zealand)|United Labour Party]] in New Zealand which had a remnant made up of moderates who did not join the new, more radical, [[Social Democratic Party (New Zealand)|Social Democratic Party]].<ref>{{cite book |chapter-url= http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/1966/political-parties/page-15 |title=[[An Encyclopaedia of New Zealand]] |chapter=Social Democratic Party | first=Bernard John |last=Foster |publisher=[[Ministry for Culture and Heritage|Ministry for Culture and Heritage / Te Manatū Taonga]] | editor-first=A. H. |editor-last=McLintock |editor-link=Alexander Hare McLintock |accessdate= 9 December 2015 |origyear=First published in 1966 |date=}}</ref> * [[Liberal Party (UK, 1989)]] * [[Communist Party of Britain]] * [[National Party (South Africa)]] under leadership of [[DF Malan]] after formation of [[United Party (South Africa)]]. * [[New National Party (South Africa)]] the new name of what remained of [[National Party (South Africa)]] under the leadership of [[FW de Klerk]] and [[Marthinus van Schalkwyk]]. * [[Progressive Canadian Party]], under [[Ernie Schreiber]] and now [[Sinclair Stevens]], the remnants of the former [[Progressive Conservative Party of Canada]] that opposed the merger with the [[Canadian Alliance]]. * The ''Rassemblement-UMP'' (Gathering-Union for a Popular Movement) is an ephemeral French legislative group, led by former Prime Minister [[François Fillon]], which split from the [[Union for a Popular Movement]] on November 2012 after the internal contestation which followed the election of the party's president. Created on November the 27, 2012, this dissident group has been reintegrated in the UMP's parlementary group after negotiations between the two rivals on January the 16, 2013.<ref>http://www.france24.com/en/20121127-media-mediawatch-ump-rump-fillon-cope</ref><ref>http://tempsreel.nouvelobs.com/politique/20130115.OBS5401/le-r-ump-c-est-bel-et-bien-fini.html</ref>
